        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1816_05_06_page01.jpg"/>
                <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
                <opener>
                    <dateline><!--If there's no date line, omit this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                        <name type="place" ref="Id_where"/>
                        <date when="1816-05-06"/>May 06, 1816<lb/></dateline>
                </opener>
            <p> My dear Madam, I am <choice><orig>asham<lb/>
                ed</orig><reg>ashamed</reg></choice>of having kept you so long<lb/>
                in ignorance of what you<lb/>
                must be anxious to know<lb/>
                the safe arrival of the two<lb/>
                shawls -- they arrived a<lb/>
                month ago in <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/tgn/7001181">Ireland</placeName> but<lb/>
                they had to travel from <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/tgn/7012112"><choice><orig>Bel<lb/>
                    fast</orig><reg>Belfast</reg></choice></placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/tgn/7001306">to <placeName>Dublin</placeName> &amp; from <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/tgn/7001306">Dublin</placeName><lb/>
                to me - The fact is they have<lb/>
                been a month at my <choice><orig>bro<lb/>
                    ther</orig><reg>brother</reg></choice><persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeC1">Sneyds</persName> house in <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/tgn/7001306"><choice><orig>Dub<lb/>
                        lin</orig><reg>Dublin</reg></choice></placeName>and he was so much<lb/>
                in misery about the<lb/>
                <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1816_05_06_page02.jpg"/>              
                health of his wife that he<lb/>
                would never answer this<lb/>
                simple question <quote>"Are the<lb/>
                    shawls safe at your house<lb/>
                    or not?" --</quote><lb/></p>
                <p> They have never yet blessed<lb/>
                    my eyes but <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeC1">Sneyd</persName> who<lb/>
                    is a mighty good judge<lb/>
                    lets me know <hi rend="underline">this morning</hi><lb/>
                    in these words<lb/></p>
                <p> <quote><hi rend="underline">"Your shawls are safe &amp;<lb/>
                    handsome"--</hi></quote>--<lb/></p>
                <p> I now send you <unclear>xxxxxx</unclear><lb/>
                    a note to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HoarF1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Hoare</persName><lb/>
                    begging them to pay to<lb/>
                    <add><persName ref="./Personography.xml#IndeX1">Mr. Indes</persName> must present the note himself</add><lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xmlIndeX1">Mr. Indes</persName> L11 - 11 - 0 -  The<lb/>
                    amount I believe of my<lb/>
                    debt to you for the shawls<lb/>
                <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1816_05_06_page03.jpg"/>               
                    - I think you said <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. E's</persName> was<lb/>
                    four guineas and a half<lb/>
                    and mine six guineas<lb/>
                and a half. -- but <choice><orig>unluck<lb/>
                    ily</orig><reg>unluckily</reg></choice> I cannot find your<lb/>
                    letter. If I mistake let me<lb/>
                    know and I will send<lb/>
                    you the balance when I<lb/>
                    pay for the shoes - I wish<lb/>
                    you had mentioned how<lb/>
                    much I am in your debt<lb/>
                    for them? - I have been<lb/>
                    very anxious to send you<lb/>
                    the money for the shawls<lb/>
                but waited from day <choice><orig>to<lb/>
                    day</orig><reg>today</reg></choice>to hear of them --<lb/></p>
                <p> If you send the shoes &amp;<lb/>
                <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1816_05_06_page04.jpg"/>               
                    boots packed up in a brown<lb/>
                    paper parcel to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HuntX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Hunters</persName><lb/>
                    directed to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Miss E</persName>- to wait<lb/>
                    till called for I think in<lb/>
                    the course of the next<lb/>
                    month a friend will<lb/>
                    call &amp; bring them over<lb/></p>
            <p> -- Pray dont vex <choice><orig>your<lb/>
                self</orig><reg>yourself</reg></choice>at having missed one<lb/>
                opportunity for I know<lb/>
                it was not likely they could<lb/>
                be in time for that &amp; am<lb/>
                in no hurry.<lb/></p>
                <p> I beg you will make<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MileX2">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Miles</persName> Miles tell you <add>honestly</add> what he<lb/>
                hears said about <title ref="https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q78219472">Comic <choice><orig>Dra<lb/>
                    mas</orig><reg>Dramas</reg></choice></title>of mine which are just<lb/>
                    coming out - Let him call at<lb/>
                    <placeName>Hunters</placeName> for a copy for you<lb/>
                    or for himself -- The same thing <lb/></p>
                <p> My father has been rather<lb/>
                    better these last 3 days<lb/></p>      
             <closer> 
                 I am Dear Madam yours sincerely<lb/>
                 <persName xml:id="EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth<lb/></persName>
                </closer>
